Title: THE FOUR OLDS
Credit: sc03 THE BARN NET + sc06 THE SEIZURE — comedy calibration, parentheticals live
Draft date: 2026-07-12 10:55

INT. DAWES BARN - NIGHT

In the dark of the barn a hand finds a starter cord and pulls it hard.

A sharp CLICK carries across the dark barn.

A single work light warms up over the APOLLO PROCEDURES TRAINER, a plywood-and-steel cockpit standing on blocks in the middle of the barn.

The gauges are hand-machined, every dial cut and inked and numbered by somebody at a bench.

A crew couch sits bolted into a welded cradle, tipped back the way a man lies down to land.

A triangular window looks out on a Moon painted straight onto the barn wall, gray and cratered and flaking a little at the edges.

ALONG THE BACK WALL -- spiral notebooks stand floor to roof, hundreds of them, each spine dated in the same block hand.

The bottom shelf starts in 1972.

CRICKET -- Earl Dawes, 79, a barn coat pulled over his pajamas, lowers himself into the couch and settles his back against it without looking.

He thumbs a microphone clipped to the frame and clears his throat.

CRICKET:
Net's open. Tuesday, nineteen-oh-two local.

Static rolls up out of an old field radio wired into the trainer's frame.

A drawl comes back first, slow and easy, off somewhere in East Texas.

STITCH (RADIO):
Evenin', Earl.

A dry, flat voice follows it, a man reading off a page.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Present.

The third voice lands square and clipped, an old Navy voice.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Stand by for roll.

In the barn Cricket reaches up and starts setting a row of toggle switches, one at a time.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Apollo Eighteen. Lunar descent rehearsal. Number two thousand, eight hundred and six.

Nobody laughs. Cricket just finishes his switches.

CRICKET:
Crew's aboard. Comm check, three by three.

STITCH (RADIO):
Loud and ugly, same as you.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Loud and clear.

CRICKET:
Coming up on the burn. Program's running.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Confirm, guidance is nominal on my copy.

STITCH (RADIO):
Y'all hear they put Harlan Voss in the ground Saturday.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Can the estate sale, Stitch. We're descending.

STITCH (RADIO):
I'm gettin' to it. They had damn near two hundred people out at that church, Dutch, and every last one of 'em stood up for the box, and that box — I want you to hear me — that box was veneer.

CRICKET:
Ten thousand feet. Rate looks good.

DUTCH (RADIO):
There were not two hundred. The church on County Road nine seats a hundred and ten. I measured it in oh-four for the fire panel.

STITCH (RADIO):
Hundred and ten seated. They was standin' in the vestibule and hangin' off the steps.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Then say a hundred and ten and standing room. Don't say two hundred.

CRICKET:
Three thousand. Throttle down on schedule.

STITCH (RADIO):
Man's serious his whole life, and they lay him in a box that's mostly glue anyhow. I want oak. Real oak. Put it in your book, Dutch.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Noted. Oak.
(then)
While I've got the book open. That Bus B relay is going to open on somebody one of these Tuesdays. I logged it November of eighty-nine and I have logged it every November since.

STITCH (RADIO):
Here he goes.

DUTCH (RADIO):
I'm allowed to say it. It is written down thirty-some times.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Nobody's stopping you, Dutch. We're at three thousand feet.

On the panel a needle sags off its peg and starts to drift down.

CRICKET:
Bus B's moving.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Say again.

CRICKET:
Voltage. Walking down.

DUTCH (RADIO):
(off it)
Steady, or does it stutter?

Cricket watches the needle bounce and fall, bounce and fall.

CRICKET:
Stutters.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Kick it. Low left corner, up under the panel.

Cricket brings his heel up and raps the underside of the panel, hard, low on the left.

The needle jumps, hangs a second, and climbs back up to its peg.

CRICKET:
Back up.

The radio holds quiet a beat.

DUTCH (RADIO):
November of eighty-nine.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Let it go, Dutch.

DUTCH (RADIO):
I did. I let it go thirty-seven years.

CRICKET:
Two thousand feet. Looking good.

STITCH (RADIO):
Anyhow. Oak. And I'll tell you what else, they had the wrong hymn. Had the funeral hymn for a Methodist and Harlan was Baptist his whole —

DUTCH (RADIO):
You'd know about missing a service. You missed a net. March of last year. I have you down as an absence.

STITCH (RADIO):
I had a hip put in me, Dutch. They had me on the good drugs. I called Earl from the bed.

CRICKET:
You did. You sang.

STITCH (RADIO):
(dry)
So take the absence off, Dutch. I was right there on the line.

CRICKET:
One thousand feet.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Quiet down, both of you, we're coming in.

STITCH (RADIO):
Comin' in where, Gunny. It's the same Moon it was last Tuesday. After fifty years of Tuesdays that Moon is not gonna jump out from behind nothin'.

CRICKET:
Five hundred.
(then)
Three hundred.

The chatter stops. Nobody calls for it and nobody says why.

Cricket's eyes stay on the painted Moon in the window.

CRICKET:
A hundred feet. Kicking up a little dust.
(then)
Forty feet.
(then)
Drifting forward a hair.

A small blue bulb on the panel comes on.

CRICKET:
Contact light. Engine stop.

The barn holds dead still. The work light hums over the couch.

STITCH (RADIO):
You come in a touch hot on the throttle there at the end, Earl.

GUNNY (RADIO):
The man is on the ground, Colonel.

CRICKET:
Crew's down. Safe and sound.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Logged. Contact, nineteen forty-one.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Net closed. Same time Tuesday.

CRICKET:
God willing.

Two clicks of dead-key static come across the radio.

Cricket keys the mic twice in answer, and one after another the others key back, two clicks each, until the field radio drops to hiss.

He reaches over to the workbench, lifts down a fresh spiral notebook, and clicks a ballpoint.

He prints it out slow in block letters that read T+2,806. BUS B CORRECTED. CONTACT 19:41. CREW PRESENT BY RADIO.

He slides the notebook onto the back-wall shelf and runs his thumb down the dated spines, from this year back toward the bottom.

He kills the work light and hooks a padlock through the door hasp, then gives it one pull to be sure.

Across the yard the farmhouse stands dark, not one light on inside it.

EXT. DAWES FARM - DAY

Two black SUVs and a county flatbed climb the gravel drive toward the Dawes farmhouse and barn.

In the lead SUV a phone sits in a dashboard mount, a voice coming off the speaker, tinny and bored.

BOSS (RADIO):
One verified recovery on the books by Saturday, or your office rolls into Lincoln's. That's the whole conversation, Pell.

In the passenger seat rides PELL, 50s, his lanyard squared on a pressed shirt and a clipboard flat on his knee.

PELL:
You'll have it.

He taps the phone off and checks his hair in the visor mirror, turning his chin one way, then the other.

He steps out of the SUV already smiling.

CRICKET stands square in the open barn doorway, Earl Dawes, 79, the painted Moon on the wall behind him.

Two movers in gloves wait at the flatbed with a dolly.

WADE hangs back by the porch steps, a county deputy in his forties, his hat already off and held in both hands.

Pell walks the length of the barn with the clipboard up, looking at the joints in the roof beams.

PELL:
Somebody framed this to last. You don't see the old peg work anymore.

He clicks his pen and starts down the inventory.

PELL:
(reading)
One crew couch. One cradle assembly, welded. One altitude indicator—

CRICKET:
Attitude.

Pell stops, pen up.

He draws a neat line through the word and prints above it.

PELL:
Noted.

CRICKET:
It was surplus. Nineteen seventy-five. Told it'd be scrapped otherwise.

PELL:
(not looking up)
Paperwork says otherwise.

A mover presses an orange sticker onto the trainer's frame and Pell smooths it flat with his thumb.

The sticker reads LUNAR HERITAGE NEUTRALIZATION ACCORD -- EX-NASA ASSET RECOVERY.

Pell drifts to the back wall and pulls down one spiral notebook, thumbs it open.

Three pages of grid-ruled block printing pass under his thumb.

PELL:
Personal papers.
(then)
No salvage value. Leave them.

He pushes the notebook back onto the shelf crooked and moves on.

At the dolly a mover cracks his knuckle on a bolt head and shakes out his hand.

Cricket reaches to the pegboard, takes down a socket, and holds it out.

The mover takes it without looking at him and fits it to the bolt.

The two movers track back and forth across the porch, their boots on boards painted only a few days back.

Cricket watches the dolly take the weight of the couch.

CRICKET:
(quiet, hard)
Not one of you ever built a thing out here. Now it's all yours.

Pell stops writing and looks at him for the first time.

PELL:
You didn't build this either, Mr. Dawes. Nineteen seventy-five it should've gone back to NASA, and it never did, and nobody asked why for fifty years. It was never yours. Paperwork just took its time getting here.

Cricket says nothing.

The dolly turns for the open doors, and Cricket steps into the gap and sets his feet.

CRICKET:
(to Wade)
You'll have to move me, Wade.

Wade sets his hat on the porch rail and comes down the steps slow.

WADE:
Earl.

He takes Cricket by both arms, gentle, and walks him three steps to the side, and Cricket lets him.

The dolly rolls past the two of them and out into the daylight.

Wade stays in close at his shoulder, voice down, while the movers load.

WADE:
(low)
Federal list came down Tuesday. County don't see a dime off it. Nobody does.

CRICKET:
Where's it go.

WADE:
Warehouse outside Lincoln, is what I hear. Same one as the rest of it.
(then)
There's a window to put in an appeal. It's open till four.

Inside the barn a clean rectangle of floor shows where the trainer stood, four bolt holes at its corners.

Cricket steps to the edge of the rectangle and stops.

He presses one hand hard to the back of his neck, takes one breath, and straightens.

Pell pulls the SUV door open and turns back with a smile for the whole yard.

PELL:
Folks, I know change feels sudden. But as the Accord reminds us -- harmony is a verb.

The SUVs and the flatbed pull out and head down the drive.

On the workbench the old field radio sits where they left it, still wired in.

Cricket crosses to it, lowers himself onto the stool, and thumbs the microphone.

CRICKET:
Net's open. Wednesday.

Three voices come back fast, one climbing over the other.

STITCH (RADIO):
Here.

DUTCH (RADIO):
Present.

GUNNY (RADIO):
Standing by.

Cricket reaches up and pulls the work light on over the empty rectangle.
